# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aeolipile
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] Drachmann was born in Copenhagen in 1891, the son of classicist Anders Bjørn Drachmann (1860–1935) and teacher Ellen Sophie Drachmann (née Bentzon, 1866–1948).
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] He studied classical philology and English language and literature at the University of Copenhagen from 1909 to 1915.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] Afterward, he took a job as a librarian at the Copenhagen University Library (one of the two most important libraries in Denmark), for which he worked from 1917 until 1956.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] He spent nine months in 1926–1927 in the United States as a fellow of the American-Scandinavian Foundation, working in the John Crerar Library and the Library of Congress, and subsequently introduced some American library processes to Denmark, including photocopying.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] In 1943, he became chief librarian at the University Library.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] In 1948, he received a PhD studying ancient pneumatics.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] In 1956 he retired to focus full-time on research.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] Starting in the 1930s, Drachmann wrote scholarly papers, primarily on ancient technology, and papers on library science.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] From 1928–1949 he edited the *Index Medicus Danicus*, a card-index bibliography of Danish medical literature.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] In the 1950s he was an editor of *Centaurus*, in which many of his papers were also published.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] He was a member of several learned societies.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] Drachmann's research focused on medicine, natural sciences and technology in antiquity.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] He wrote books on "pneumatic medicine", oil mills, ancient mechanics and Caesar's Rhine bridges, as well as several articles for the *Realencyclopädie der classischen Altertumswissenschaft* and the *Dictionary of Scientific Biography*.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] Drachmann's 1963 book *Mechanical Technology of Greek and Roman Antiquity* consisted of a critical translation and commentary on Hero of Alexandria's *Mechanics* (from Qusṭā ibn Lūqā's Arabic translation), alongside study of other works by Hero, pseudo-Aristotle, Vitruvius, and Oribasius.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] In mechanics, Drachmann's method combined careful textual analysis with practical mechanical experiments and constructions.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] His writing was characterized by an insightful but unpretentious and commonsense style.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] In 1971 he received the Leonardo da Vinci Medal for his scholarship in the history of technology.
[src:aeolipile/a-g-drachmann] Drachmann also studied English literature, Danish folk tales and ornithology.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:aeolipile/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:aeolipile/aeolus] In Greek mythology, **Aiolos**, transcribed as **Aeolus** (/ˈiːələs/ ⓘ; Ancient Greek: Αἴολος [ǎi̯.olos]; Modern Greek: Αίολος [ˈe.olos] ⓘ) refers to three characters.
[src:aeolipile/aeolus] These three are often difficult to tell apart, and even the ancient mythographers appear to have been perplexed about which Aeolus was which.
[src:aeolipile/aeolus] Diodorus Siculus made an attempt to define each of these three (although it is clear that he also became muddled), and his opinion is followed here.
[src:aeolipile/aeolus] All three men named Aeolus appear to be connected genealogically, although the precise relationship, especially regarding the second and third Aeolus, is often ambiguous as their identities seem to have been merged by many ancient writers.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Nicknamed the "Bride of the Mediterranean" and "Pearl of the Mediterranean Coast", the city is a popular tourist destination and a major industrial centre.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It is the sixth-largest city in the Arab world, seventh-largest city in the Middle East, and the eleventh-largest city in Africa.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The capital of the Alexandria Governorate, Alexandria is considered an industrial hub and is home to the Alexandria Shipyard.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city also has a large financial sector, and its ancient port Alexandria is one of the busiest ports in the country.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria is the host city of the annual Alexandria Mediterranean Countries Film Festival, held at the Bibliotheca Alexandrina.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city is also the home of the Alexandria Opera House, the Alexandria Museum of Fine Arts and the Alexandria National Museum.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city hosts many sporting events, and is the home of the association football club Al Ittihad.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria extends beyond its administrative municipal city limits as well as its urban agglomeration, with a population of 6,100,000 in 2023 over an area of 1,661 square kilometres (641 sq mi).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was originally established near an ancient Egyptian settlement named Rhacotis, which later became its Egyptian quarter.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city was made the capital of the Ptolemaic Kingdom and became the foremost commercial, intellectual, and cultural centre for much of the Hellenistic age and late antiquity; at one time, it was the most populous city in the ancient world.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was best known for the Lighthouse of Alexandria (*Pharos*), one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World; its Great Library, the largest in the ancient world; and the Catacombs of Kom El Shoqafa, one of the Seven Wonders of the Middle Ages.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria retained its status as one of the leading cities of the Mediterranean world for almost a millennium, serving as the Egyptian capital until a new capital was founded at Fustat, now part of Cairo.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city was a major hub of early Christianity and hosted the Patriarchate of Alexandria, one of the leading Christian centers in the Eastern Roman Empire; the modern Coptic Orthodox Church and the Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria both lay claim to this ancient heritage.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] By the mid-seventh century, the city continued to serve as a trading hub and naval base.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] From the late 18th century, it was a major centre of the international shipping industry and one of the most important trading centers in the world, owing to the easy overland connection between the Mediterranean and Red Seas and the lucrative trade in Egyptian cotton.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria's rebirth began in the early 19th century under Muhammad Ali, considered the founder of modern Egypt, who implemented infrastructure projects and modernisation efforts.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was located on the earlier Egyptian settlement, which was called Rhacotis (Ancient Greek: Ῥακῶτις, romanized: *Rhakôtis*), the Hellenised form of Egyptian *r-ꜥ-qd(y)t* (Bohairic Coptic: ⲣⲁⲕⲟϯ, romanized: *Rakoti*).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Some of the Alexandrian and Greek populaces, e.g., Hypsicles, also referred to the city as *Alexándreia hḗ prós Aígypton* (Ἀλεξάνδρεια ἡ πρός Αἴγυπτον, "Alexandria near Egypt").
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In the course of Roman rule in Egypt, the city's name was Latinised as *Alexandrēa ad Aegyptum*.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In Coptic, the city continued to be referred to by its earlier name (Rakoti), with only a few exceptions.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Radiocarbon dating of seashell fragments and lead contamination show human activity at the location during the period of the Old Kingdom (27th–21st centuries BC) and again in the period 1000–800 BC, followed by the absence of activity after that.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] From ancient sources it is known there existed a trading post at this location during the time of Rameses the Great for trade with Crete, but it had long been lost by the time of Alexander's arrival.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] A small Egyptian fishing village named Rhakotis (Egyptian: *rꜥ-qdy.t*, 'That which is built up') existed since the 13th century BC in the vicinity and eventually grew into the Egyptian quarter of the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Just east of Alexandria (where Abu Qir Bay is now), there were in ancient times marshland and several islands.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] As early as the 7th century BC, there existed important port cities of Canopus and Heracleion.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The latter was recently rediscovered underwater.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was founded by Alexander the Great in April 331 BC as Ἀλεξάνδρεια (*Alexandreia*), as one of his many city foundations.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] After he captured the Egyptian Satrapy from the Persians, Alexander wanted to build a large Greek city on Egypt's coast that would bear his name.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] He chose the site of Alexandria, envisioning the building of a causeway to the nearby island of Pharos that would generate two great natural harbours.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was intended to supersede the older Greek colony of Naucratis as a Hellenistic center in Egypt and to be the link between Greece and the rich Nile valley.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] A few months after the foundation, Alexander left Egypt and never returned to the city during his life.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] After Alexander's departure, his viceroy Cleomenes continued the expansion.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The architect Dinocrates of Rhodes designed the city, using a Hippodamian grid plan.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Following Alexander's death in 323 BC, his general Ptolemy Lagides took possession of Egypt and brought Alexander's body to Egypt with him.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Ptolemy at first ruled from the old Egyptian capital of Memphis.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In 322/321 BC he had Cleomenes executed.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Finally, in 305 BC, Ptolemy declared himself Pharaoh as Ptolemy I Soter ("Savior") and moved his capital to Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Although Cleomenes was mainly in charge of overseeing Alexandria's early development, the *Heptastadion* and the mainland quarters seem to have been primarily Ptolemaic work.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Inheriting the trade of ruined Tyre and becoming the centre of the new commerce between Europe and the Arabian and Indian East, the city grew in less than a generation to be larger than Carthage.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In one century, Alexandria had become the largest city in the world and, for some centuries more, was second only to Rome.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It became Egypt's main Greek city, with Greek people from diverse backgrounds.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Septuagint, a Greek version of the Tanakh, was produced there.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] By the time of Augustus, the city grid encompassed an area of 10 km2 (3.9 sq mi), and the total population during the Roman principate was around 500,000–600,000, which would wax and wane in the course of the next four centuries under Roman rule.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This event has been called the Alexandrian pogroms.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The violence was quelled after Caligula intervened and had the Roman governor, Flaccus, removed from the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In 115 AD, large parts of Alexandria were destroyed during the Diaspora revolt, which gave Hadrian and his architect, Decriannus, an opportunity to rebuild it.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In 215 AD, the emperor Caracalla visited the city and, because of some insulting satires that the inhabitants had directed at him, abruptly commanded his troops to put to death all youths capable of bearing arms.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] On 21 July 365 AD, Alexandria was devastated by a tsunami (365 Crete earthquake), an event annually commemorated years later as a "day of horror".
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria was an important city in the early history of Christianity, and played a key role in the development of Christian theology.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In 619, Alexandria fell to the Sassanid Persians.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city was mostly uninjured by the conquest and a new palace called *Tarawus* was erected in the eastern part of the city, later known as Qasr Faris, "fort of the Persians".
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Although the Byzantine emperor Heraclius recovered it in 629, in 641 the Arabs under the general 'Amr ibn al-'As invaded it during the Muslim conquest of Egypt, after a siege that lasted 14 months.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The first Arab governor of Egypt recorded to have visited Alexandria was Utba ibn Abi Sufyan, who strengthened the Arab presence and built a governor's palace in the city in 664–665.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In reference to Alexandria, Ibn Battuta speaks of a number of Muslim saints that resided in the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] One such saint was Imam Borhan Oddin El Aaraj, who was said to perform miracles.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Another notable figure was Yaqut al-'Arshi, a disciple of Abu Abbas El Mursi.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Ibn Battuta also writes about Abu 'Abdallah al-Murshidi, a saint that lived in the Minyat of Ibn Murshed.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Although al-Murshidi lived in seclusion, Ibn Battuta writes that he was regularly visited by crowds, high state officials, and even by the Sultan of Egypt at the time, al-Nasir Muhammad.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Ibn Battuta also visited the Pharos lighthouse on two occasions: in 1326 he found it to be partly in ruins and in 1349 it had deteriorated to the point that it was no longer possible to enter.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Throughout the late medieval period, Alexandria re-emerged as a major metropolis and the most important commercial port in Egypt and one of the most important in the Mediterranean.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Jewish traveller Benjamin of Tudela even described it as "a trading market for all nations".
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Indeed, Alexandria was the outlet for all goods coming from Arabia, such as incense, and from India and South-East Asia, such as spices (pepper, cloves, cinnamon, etc.), precious stones, pearls and exotic woods like brazilwood.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] But it was also the outlet for goods from Africa, such as ivory and precious woods.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] These goods arrived in Alexandria after passing through Aden on their way to the Red Sea, then headed up the Red Sea to be unloaded in the port of Aydhab.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] From Aydhab, a caravan took the goods to the Nile, probably to the town of Qus.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] From there, the goods sailed to Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] These goods then found their way to the Alexandria market alongside Egyptian products.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This route was the cheapest and fastest in comparison with the land routes that reached the Mediterranean from Syria or Constantinople.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Latin merchants (Venetians, Genoese, Pisans, Catalans, Provençals, etc.) thus entered this market.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] As early as the 12th century, the major trading cities had funduqs and consuls in Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] A funduq, in this context is an area, often fortified, within the city dedicated to the community of a trading nation under the authority of a consul.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The consul was responsible for adjudicating disputes between merchants of his nation, and also when a subject of the sultan lodged a complaint against a merchant of their nation.The terms of this installation were often set out in treaties between the sultans and the consuls.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] These treaties were part of a policy pursued by the early Mamluk sultans, who encouraged the arrival of merchants from Europe in Alexandria, since this trade not only brought the sultan considerable revenue, but also enabled him to obtain supplies of wood and iron from Europe.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Later, in the 14th century, the Latin trade in Alexandria was also important for the sultans, as it enabled them to obtain supplies of mameluks (slave-soldiers) often sold by Genoese merchants.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] As this trade was very important to the sultans, they were keen to control the city's institutions.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Indeed, in Alexandria, in addition to an Emir (governor), the sultan sent a customs inspector who answered directly to the *nazir al-khas* (person in charge of managing the sultan's patrimony).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Customs was not only responsible for collecting customs duties, but also for the security of the port and its warehouses.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria customs also played a role in commercial arbitration and was the preferred circuit for the sale of products brought in by the merchants, which took place at auction.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] These sales were set up to encourage the merchants to sell their products to or through the sultan, rather than selling them freely on the city's markets.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Latin merchants also had jurisdictional privileges : in addition to being judged by their consul if a subject of the sultan lodged a complaint against them, Latin merchants could not be judged by the qadis (civil judges) but had to be judged by the mazalim (the sultan's courts).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria lost much of its importance in international trade after Portuguese navigators discovered a new sea route to India in the late 15th century.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This reduced the amount of goods that needed to be transported through the Alexandrian port, as well as the Mamluks' political power.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] After the Battle of Ridaniya in 1517, the city was conquered by the Ottoman Turks and remained under Ottoman rule until 1798.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria lost much of its former importance to the Egyptian port city of Rosetta during the 9th to 18th centuries, and it only regained its former prominence with the construction of the Mahmoudiyah Canal in 1820.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria figured prominently in the military operations of Napoleon's expedition to Egypt in 1798.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] French troops stormed the city on 2 July 1798, and it remained in their hands until the arrival of a British expedition in 1801.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The British won a considerable victory over the French at the Battle of Alexandria on 21 March 1801, following which they besieged the city, which fell to them on 2 September 1801.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Muhammad Ali, the Ottoman governor of Egypt, began rebuilding and redevelopment around 1810 and, by 1850, Alexandria had returned to something akin to its former glory.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Egypt turned to Europe in their effort to modernise the country.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Greeks, followed by other Europeans and others, began moving to the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In the early 20th century, the city became a home for novelists and poets.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In July 1882, the city came under bombardment from British naval forces and was occupied.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In July 1954, the city was a target of an Israeli bombing campaign that later became known as the Lavon Affair.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] On 26 October 1954, Alexandria's Mansheya Square was the site of a failed assassination attempt on Gamal Abdel Nasser.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Europeans began leaving Alexandria following the 1956 Suez Crisis that led to an outburst of Arab nationalism.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The nationalisation of property by Nasser, which reached its highest point in 1961, drove out nearly all the rest.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria is located in the country of Egypt, on the southern coast of the Mediterranean.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It is a densely populated city; its core areas belie its large administrative area.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city's geology consists of soil sediments, oolitic sand and clay, oolitic limestone (from the Middle Miocene), grey shelly dolomite, marly dolomite, oncolitic limestone and dolomite, and as well as shelly limestone.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Notes: 2020 CAPMAS projection based on 2017 revised census figures, may differ significantly from 2017 census preliminary tabulations.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The 14 kisms were reported simply as *Alexandria city* by CAPMAS in 2006 but given explosive growth definitions, likely informal, may have changed or may be set to change.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Same area with 12 kisms existed in 1996.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has a borderline hot steppe and hot desert climate (Köppen climate classification: *BSh*/*BWh*).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Like the rest of Egypt's northern coast, the prevailing north wind, blowing across the Mediterranean, gives the city a less severe climate than the desert hinterland.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Rafah and Alexandria are the wettest places in Egypt; the other wettest places are Rosetta, Baltim, Kafr el-Dawwar, and Mersa Matruh.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria experiences violent storms, rain and sometimes sleet and hail during the cooler months; these events, combined with a poor drainage system, have been responsible for occasional flooding in the city in the past though they rarely occur anymore.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] July and August are the hottest and driest months of the year, with an average daily maximum temperature of 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Port Said, Kosseir, Baltim, Damietta and Alexandria have the least temperature variation in Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The highest recorded temperature was 45 °C (113 °F) on 30 May 1961, and the coldest recorded temperature was 0 °C (32 °F) on 31 January 1994.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The annual temperature would increase by 2.8 °C (5.0 °F), and the temperature of the warmest and the coldest month by 2.9 °C (5.2 °F) and 3.1 °C (5.6 °F).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] According to Climate Action Tracker, the current warming trajectory appears consistent with 2.7 °C (4.9 °F), which closely matches RCP 4.5.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Due to its location on a Nile river delta, Alexandria is one of the most vulnerable cities to sea level rise in the entire world.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] According to some estimates, hundreds of thousands of people in its low-lying areas may already have to be relocated before 2030.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Additional accounting for the "low-probability, high-damage events" may increase aggregate risks to US$187 billion for the "moderate" RCP4.5, US$206 billion for RCP8.5 and US$397 billion under the high-end ice sheet instability scenario.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In every single estimate, Alexandria alone bears around half of these costs.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Since sea level rise would continue for about 10,000 years under every scenario of climate change, future costs of sea level rise would only increase, especially without adaptation measures.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Recent studies published in Earth's Future by the American Geophysical Union indicate that rising sea levels are causing increases in coastal aquifer levels, reaching building foundations and accelerating their corrosion and potential collapse.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The study predicts that in 2025, more than 7000 buildings in Alexandria will be at risk of collapse due to these groundwater processes.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] "Alexandria") was the old city that was absorbed into Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Brucheum was the Royal or Greek quarter and formed the most magnificent portion of the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] , Brucheum was enlarged by the addition of an official quarter, making four regions in all.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city was laid out as a grid of parallel streets, each of which had an attendant subterranean canal.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Jewish quarter was the northeast portion of the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Two main streets, lined with colonnades and said to have been each about 60 m (200 ft) wide, intersected in the centre of the city, close to the point where the Sema (or Soma) of Alexander (his Mausoleum) rose.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This point is very near the present mosque of Nebi Daniel; the line of the great East–West "Canopic" street is also present in modern-day Alexandria, having only slightly diverged from the line of the modern Boulevard de Rosette (now Sharae Fouad).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Traces of its pavement and canal have been found near the Rosetta Gate, but remnants of streets and canals were exposed in 1899 by German excavators outside the east fortifications, which lie well within the area of the ancient city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria consisted originally of little more than the island of Pharos, which was joined to the mainland by a 1,260 m-long (4,130 ft) mole and called the *Heptastadion* ("seven stadia"—a *stadium* was a Greek unit of length measuring approximately 180 m or 590 ft).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The end of this abutted on the land at the head of the present Grand Square, where the "Moon Gate" rose.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] All that now lies between that point and the modern "Ras al-Tin" quarter is built on the silt which gradually widened and obliterated this mole.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Ras al-Tin quarter represents all that is left of the island of Pharos, the site of the actual lighthouse having been weathered away by the sea.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] On the east of the mole was the Great Harbour, now an open bay; on the west lay the port of Eunostos, with its inner basin Kibotos, now vastly enlarged to form the modern harbour.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In Strabo's time (latter half of the 1st century BC), the principal buildings were as follows, enumerated as they were to be seen from a ship entering the Great Harbour.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Great Theater, on the modern Hospital Hill near the Ramleh station.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This was used by Julius Caesar as a fortress, where he withstood a siege from the city mob after he took Egypt after the battle of Pharsalus.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Behind the Emporium rose the Great Caesareum, by which stood the two great obelisks which became known as "Cleopatra's Needles" and were transported to New York City and London.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This temple became, in time, the Patriarchal Church, though some ancient remains of the temple have been discovered.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The actual Caesareum, the parts not eroded by the waves, lies under the houses lining the new seawall.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Gymnasium and the Palaestra are both inland, near the Boulevard de Rosette in the eastern half of the town; sites unknown.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Mausolea of Alexander (Soma) and the Ptolemies in one ring-fence, near the point of intersection of the two main streets.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Musaeum with its famous Library and theater in the same region; site unknown.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Serapeum of Alexandria, the most famous of all Alexandrian temples.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Strabo tells that this stood in the west of the city; and recent discoveries go far as to place it near "Pompey's Pillar", which was an independent monument erected to commemorate Diocletian's siege of the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The names of a few other public buildings on the mainland are known, but there is little information as to their actual position.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] None, however, are as famous as the building that stood on the eastern point of Pharos island.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] There, The Great Lighthouse, one of the Seven Wonders of the World, reputed to be 138 m (453 ft) high, was situated.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The first Ptolemy began the project, and the second Ptolemy (Ptolemy II Philadelphus) completed it, at a total cost of 800 talents.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It took 12 years to complete and served as a prototype for all later lighthouses in the world.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The light was produced by a furnace at the top and the tower was built mostly with solid blocks of limestone.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Pharos lighthouse was destroyed by an earthquake in the 14th century, making it the second longest surviving ancient wonder, after the Great Pyramid of Giza.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] A temple of Hephaestus also stood on Pharos at the head of the mole.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In the 1st century, the population of Alexandria contained over 180,000 adult male citizens, according to a census dated from 32 AD, in addition to a large number of freedmen, women, children and slaves.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Estimates of the total population range from 216,000 to 500,000, making it one of the largest cities ever built before the Industrial Revolution and the largest pre-industrial city that was not an imperial capital.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] "Pompey's Pillar, a Roman triumphal column, is one of the best-known ancient monuments still standing in Alexandria today.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It is located on Alexandria's ancient acropolis—a modest hill located adjacent to the city's Arab cemetery—and was originally part of a temple colonnade.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Including its pedestal, it is 30 m (99 ft) high; the shaft is of polished red granite, 2.7 m (8.9 ft) in diameter at the base, tapering to 2.4 m (7.9 ft) at the top.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The shaft is 88 ft (27 m) high and made out of a single piece of granite.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Its volume is 132 m3 (4,662 cu ft) and weight approximately 396 tons.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Pompey's Pillar may have been erected using the same methods that were used to erect the ancient obelisks.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Roger Hopkins and Mark Lehrner conducted several obelisk erecting experiments including a successful attempt to erect a 25-ton obelisk in 1999.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The catacombs were long forgotten by the citizens until they were discovered by accident in 1900.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The most extensive ancient excavation currently being conducted in Alexandria is known as Kom El Deka.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It has revealed the ancient city's well-preserved theater, and the remains of its Roman-era baths.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Alexandria Naval Unknown Soldier Memorial is a prominent historical monument located in the Manshaya district along the corniche.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Built in 1933 to honor Khedive Ismail, and a statue of him was erected at the top of the monument.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It was later transformed into the Monument to the Unknown Soldier in 1965, and the statue of Khedive Ismail was removed.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The monument is distinguished by its location overlooking the Mediterranean Sea, which has witnessed the glories and heroic deeds of the Egyptian Navy throughout history, and serves as a memorial to its martyrs.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The temple was built in the Ptolemy era and dedicated to Osiris, which finished the construction of Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It is located in Abusir, the western suburb of Alexandria in Borg el Arab city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Only the outer wall and the pylons remain from the temple.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] There is evidence to prove that sacred animals were worshiped there.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Archaeologists found an animal necropolis near the temple.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Remains of a Christian church show that the temple was used as a church in later centuries.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Also found in the same area are remains of public baths built by the emperor Justinian, a seawall, quays and a bridge.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Near the beach side of the area, there are the remains of a tower built by Ptolemy II Philadelphus.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The tower was an exact scale replica of the destroyed Alexandrine Pharos Lighthouse.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Citadel of Qaitbay is a defensive fortress located on the Mediterranean sea coast.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It was established in 1477 AD (882 AH) by the mamluk Sultan Al-Ashraf Sayf al-Din Qa'it Bay.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Citadel is located on the eastern side of the northern tip of Pharos Island at the mouth of the Eastern Harbour.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It was erected on the exact site of the famous Lighthouse of Alexandria, which was one of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It was built on an area of 17,550 square metres.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Persistent efforts have been made to explore the antiquities of Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Encouragement and help have been given by the local Archaeological Society and by many individuals.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Excavations were performed in the city by Greeks seeking the tomb of Alexander the Great without success.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The past and present directors of the museum have been enabled from time to time to carry out systematic excavations whenever opportunity is offered; D.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Hogarth made tentative researches on behalf of the Egypt Exploration Fund and the Society for the Promotion of Hellenic Studies in 1895; and a German expedition worked for two years (1898–1899).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] But two difficulties face the would-be excavator in Alexandria: lack of space for excavation and the underwater location of some areas of interest.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Since the great and growing modern city stands immediately over the ancient one, it is almost impossible to find any considerable space in which to dig, except at enormous cost.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Cleopatra VII's royal quarters were inundated by earthquakes and tsunami, leading to gradual subsidence in the 4th century AD.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This underwater section, containing many of the most interesting sections of the Hellenistic city, including the palace quarter, has been explored since 1992 and is still being extensively investigated by the French underwater archaeologist Franck Goddio and his team.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It raised numerous artefacts, among them a noted head of Caesarion.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The remains of a temple to Isis on the sunken island of Antirhodos in the eastern port of Alexandria have been gradually discovered, excavated and identified over a period of 30 years by Goddio's team and published by the Oxford Centre for Maritime Archaeology in 2025.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Some parts of the city's port being opened up to tourists, to some controversy.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The spaces that are most open are the low grounds to northeast and southwest, where it is practically impossible to get below the Roman strata.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The most important results were those achieved by Dr.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Botti, late director of the museum, in the neighbourhood of "Pompey's Pillar", where there is a good deal of open ground.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Here, substructures of a large building or group of buildings have been exposed, which are perhaps part of the Serapeum.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Nearby, immense catacombs and *columbaria* have been opened which may have been appendages of the temple.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] These contain one very remarkable vault with curious painted reliefs, now artificially lit and open to visitors.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The objects found in these researches are in the museum, the most notable being a great basalt bull, probably once an object of cult in the Serapeum.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Other catacombs and tombs have been opened in Kom El Shoqafa (Roman) and Ras El Tin (painted).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The German excavation team found remains of a Ptolemaic colonnade and streets in the north-east of the city, but little else.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Hogarth explored part of an immense brick structure under the mound of Kom El Deka, which may have been part of the Paneum, the Mausolea, or a Roman fortress.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The making of the new foreshore led to the dredging up of remains of the Patriarchal Church; and the foundations of modern buildings are seldom laid without some objects of antiquity being discovered.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The fertilizer industry represents one of Alexandria's most strategically important economic sectors.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Major producers supply both the domestic agricultural market and international customers.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city's ammonia and nitrogen fertilizer plants have historically relied on natural gas as a feedstock for hydrogen production.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] These facilities have become central to Egypt's ambitions to develop lower-carbon industrial exports while preserving existing industrial infrastructure.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] During the 2020s, Alexandria increasingly became part of Egypt's national strategy to establish itself as a leading producer of green fuels and clean industrial products.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] A major milestone occurred in 2026 when a memorandum of understanding was signed between the Chinese company UEG, Orascom Construction, Abu Qir Fertilizers, and Alexandria Fertilizers Company (AlexFert) during the Egypt Energy Conference.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The agreement outlined plans to integrate green hydrogen into existing fertilizer production facilities in Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Under the proposal, renewable energy capacity of up to 500 megawatts from wind and solar sources would be developed to power water electrolysis systems for green hydrogen production.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Instead of constructing entirely new ammonia complexes, the project would utilize existing fertilizer plants and gradually replace part of the natural-gas-derived hydrogen currently used in production.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] This approach allows the city to leverage its established industrial base while reducing carbon emissions.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The project is expected to support the production of approximately 480 tons of green ammonia per day, positioning Alexandria among emerging centers for low-carbon ammonia production in the Mediterranean region.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The initiative reflects broader global demand for low-emission industrial products, particularly in European markets where environmental standards increasingly influence purchasing decisions.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] By incorporating green hydrogen into fertilizer manufacturing, Alexandria's producers aim to access premium export markets and strengthen Egypt's competitiveness in the global energy transition.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] One of the most significant recent industrial expansions involves Prometeon, the global tire manufacturer owned by a Chinese industrial group.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The company already operates a heavy-duty tire factory in the Amreya district, with annual production capacity reaching approximately 1.2 million truck and bus tires.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] A large share of this output is exported to international markets, highlighting Alexandria's role as a manufacturing platform for global supply chains.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In 2026, the company announced plans for a major expansion program valued at nearly US$400 million.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The project includes increasing heavy-duty tire production and constructing a new passenger-car tire factory adjacent to the existing facility.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The new plant is planned to occupy approximately 180,000–200,000 square meters and is expected to produce around 1.5 million passenger-car tires annually.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has a number of higher education institutions.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria University is a public university that follows the Egyptian system of higher education.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Many of its faculties are internationally renowned, most notably the Faculty of Medicine and the Faculty of Engineering.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In addition, the Egypt-Japan University of Science and Technology in New Borg El Arab city is a research university set up in collaboration between the Japanese and Egyptian governments in 2010.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Arab Academy for Science, Technology & Maritime Transport is a semi-private educational institution that offers courses for high school, undergraduate level, and postgraduate students.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It is considered the most reputable university in Egypt after the AUC American University in Cairo because of its worldwide recognition from board of engineers at UK & ABET in US.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Université Senghor is a private French university that focuses on the teaching of humanities, politics and international relations, which mainly recruits students from the African continent.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Other institutions of higher education in Alexandria include Alexandria Institute of Technology (AIT) and Pharos University in Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In September 2023, The Greek University of Patras announced that it is opening a branch in Alexandria, in a first-of-its-kind move by a Greek higher education institution.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Greek university of Patras branch will operate two departments, one Greek-speaking and one English-speaking in the subjects of Greek culture, Greek language and Greek philosophy.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has a long history of foreign educational institutions.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The first foreign schools date to the early 19th century, when French missionaries began establishing French charitable schools to educate the Egyptians.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] As a reaction to the establishment of French religious institutions, a secular (laic) mission established Lycée el-Horreya, which initially followed a French system of education, but is currently run by the Egyptian government.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The only school in Alexandria that completely follows the French educational system is Lycée Français d'Alexandrie (École Champollion).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It is usually frequented by the children of French expatriates and diplomats in Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Italian school is the Istituto "Don Bosco".
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] There are also two German schools in Alexandria which are Deutsche Schule der Borromäerinnen (DSB of Saint Charles Borromé) and Neue Deutsche Schule Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Montessori educational system was first introduced in Alexandria in 2009 at Alexandria Montessori.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Around the 1890s, twice the percentage of women in Alexandria knew how to read compared to Cairo.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] As a result, specialist women's publications like *al-Fatāh* by Hind Nawal, the country's first women's journal, appeared.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The city's principal airport is currently Alexandria International Airport, which is located about 25 km (16 mi) away from the city centre, which is now composed of 2 Terminals.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Terminal 1 is the old terminal which was opened in February 2010 whereas Terminal 2 is the Brand New Terminal and was inaugurated in 2025.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] In addition to these, the city include other major roads such as Fouad Street, considered the oldest street in Alexandria, Suez Canal Street, El-Nabi Daniel Street, Port Said Street, Sultan Hussein Street, and the Ring Road.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria also include several highways, such as the Cairo–Alexandria Desert Road, the Cairo–Alexandria Agricultural Road, and the International Coastal Road.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria has four ports; namely the Western Port also known as *Alexandria Port*.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Also the Dekhela Port is located in the west of the Alexandria Port.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The Eastern Port which is mainly used as a yachting harbour, and Abu Qir Port at the northern east of the governorate.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] It is a commercial port for general cargo and phosphates.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria's intracity commuter rail system extends from Misr Station (Alexandria's primary intercity railway station) to Abu Qir, parallel to the tram line.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The commuter line's locomotives operate on diesel, as opposed to the overhead-electric tram.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria plays hosts to two intercity railway stations; Misr Station and Sidi Gaber railway station (in the district of Sidi Gaber in the centre of the eastern expansion in which most Alexandrines reside), both of which also serve the commuter rail line.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Intercity passenger service is operated by Egyptian National Railways.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Alexandria also includes a public bus transport network operated by the Alexandria Passenger Transport Authority, in addition to other private companies.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Muharram Bek station is considered the main bus station that includes all means of transport that connect with neighboring cities and governorates.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] Construction of the Alexandria Metro was due to begin in 2020 at a cost of $1.05 billion.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] An extensive tramway network was built in 1860 and is the oldest in Africa.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p01] The network begins at the El Raml district in the west and ends in the Victoria district in the east.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Royal Library of Alexandria, in Alexandria, Egypt, was once the largest library in the world.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] It is generally thought to have been founded at the beginning of the 3rd century BC, during the reign of Ptolemy II of Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] It was likely created after his father had built what would become the first part of the library complex, the temple of the Muses—the Museion, Greek *Μουσείον* (from which the Modern English word *museum* is derived).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] It has been reasonably established that the library, or parts of the collection, were destroyed by fire on a number of occasions (library fires were common and replacement of handwritten manuscripts was very difficult, expensive, and time-consuming).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] To this day, the details of the destruction (or destructions) remain a lively source of controversy.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Bibliotheca Alexandrina was inaugurated in 2002, near the site of the old Library.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The library hosts annually the Alexandria International Film Festival.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Alexandria National Museum was inaugurated 31 December 2003.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] It is located in a restored Italian style palace in Tariq El Horreya Street (formerly Rue Fouad), near the centre of the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] It contains about 1,800 artifacts that narrate the story of Alexandria and Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Most of these pieces came from other Egyptian museums.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The museum is housed in the old Al-Saad Bassili Pasha Palace, who was one of the wealthiest wood merchants in Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Construction on the site was first undertaken in 1926.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Graeco-Roman Museum was the city's main archeological museum, focused on artifacts from its Greco-Roman period.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] It was opened in 1892 and was closed in 2005 for extensive renovations and expansion.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The museum re-opened to the public in October 2023.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Alexandria Museum of Fine Arts is a museum for Egyptian and Middle-Eastern fine art situated in the Moharam Bek neighborhood of Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The museum houses a collection of works by Egyptian artist and a selection of works from Baroque, Romanticism, Rococo and Orientalism.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] In addition, noteworthy examples of carving, printing and sculpture from Egyptian and European artists.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Other museums in the city include the Cavafy Museum, the Museum of Fine Arts, and the Royal Jewelry Museum.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Alexandria Opera House hosts performances of classical music, Arabic music, ballet, and opera.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] During the Hellenistic period, poets evolving in the court of Ptolemy II Philadelphus (Philiscus of Corcyra, Lycophron, Alexander Aetolus, Sositheus,...) are currently known as the Alexandrian Pleiad.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Cavafy, a major Greek poet who was born and lived in Alexandria used several themes associated with this city in his work: "Alexandrian Kings", "In Alexandria, 31 B.C.", "Myres: Alexandria 340 A.D", "Kaisarion" and "The God Abandons Antony".
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The most famous mosque in Alexandria is Abu al-Abbas al-Mursi Mosque in Bahary.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Alexandria is the base of the Salafi movements in Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Al-Nour Party, which is based in the city and overwhelmingly won most of the Salafi votes in the 2011–12 parliamentary election, supports the president Abdel Fattah el-Sisi.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Alexandria was once considered the third-most important city in Christianity, after Rome and Constantinople.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Until 430, the Patriarch of Alexandria was second only to the bishop of Rome.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Church of Alexandria had jurisdiction over most of the continent of Africa.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] After the Council of Chalcedon in AD 451, the Alexandrian Church split between the Miaphysites and the Melkites.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Miaphysites went on to constitute what is known today as the Coptic Orthodox Church.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Melkites went on to constitute what is known today as the Greek Orthodox Church of Alexandria.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] In the 19th century, Catholic and Protestant missionaries converted some of the adherents of the Orthodox churches to their respective faiths.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Today the Patriarchal seat of the Pope of the Coptic Orthodox Church is Saint Mark Cathedral (though in practice the Patriarch has long resided in Cairo).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Apostolic Vicariate of Alexandria in Egypt-Heliopolis-Port Said has jurisdiction over all Latin Catholics in Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Member churches include Saint Catherine Church in Mansheya and Church of the Jesuits in Cleopatra.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Saint Mark Church in Shatby, founded as part of Collège Saint Marc, is multi-denominational and holds liturgies according to Latin Catholic, Coptic Catholic and Coptic Orthodox rites.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] In antiquity Alexandria was a major centre of the cosmopolitan religious movement called Gnosticism (today mainly remembered as a Christian heresy).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Alexandria's Jewish community declined rapidly following the 1948 Arab–Israeli War, after which negative reactions towards Zionism among Egyptians led to Jewish residents in the city, and elsewhere in Egypt, being perceived as Zionist collaborators.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Most Jewish residents of Egypt moved to the newly settled Israel, France, Brazil and other countries in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The community once numbered 50,000 but is now estimated at below 50.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The most important synagogue in Alexandria is the Eliyahu Hanavi Synagogue.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The main sport that interests Alexandrians is football, as is the case in the rest of Egypt and Africa.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Alexandria Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] It is currently used mostly for football matches and was used for the 2006 African Cup of Nations.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The stadium is the oldest stadium in Egypt, being built in 1929.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Alexandria was one of three cities that participated in hosting the African Cup of Nations in January 2006, which Egypt won.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Sea sports such as surfing, jet-skiing and water polo are practiced on a lower scale.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The Skateboarding culture in Egypt started in this city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The city is also home to the Alexandria Sporting Club, which is especially known for its basketball team, which traditionally provides the country's national team with key players.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] The city hosted the AfroBasket, the continent's most prestigious basketball tournament, on four occasions (1970, 1975, 1983, 2003).
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Alexandria is also known as the yearly starting point of Cross Egypt Challenge and a huge celebration is conducted the night before the rally starts after all the international participants arrive to the city.
[src:aeolipile/alexandria-p02] Cross Egypt Challenge is an international cross-country motorcycle and scooter rally conducted throughout the most difficult tracks and roads of Egypt.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] There are also several historical forms.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:aeolipile/ancient-greek] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens is one of the world's oldest cities, with its recorded history spanning over 3,400 years, and its earliest human presence beginning somewhere between the 11th and 7th millennia BC.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] According to Greek mythology, the city was named after Athena, the ancient Greek goddess of wisdom, but modern scholars generally agree that the goddess took her name after the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Classical Athens was one of the most powerful city-states in ancient Greece.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It was a centre for Ancient Greek democracy, the arts, education and philosophy, and was highly influential throughout the Hellenistic world and the European continent, particularly in ancient Rome.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] For this reason it is often regarded as the cradle of Western civilisation and the birthplace of democracy in its own right independently from the rest of Greece.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In modern times Athens is a large cosmopolitan metropolis and central to economic, financial, industrial, maritime, political and cultural life in Greece.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It is a Beta (+) – status global city according to the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, and is one of the biggest economic centres in Southeast Europe.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It also has a large financial sector, and its port Piraeus is both the second-busiest passenger port in Europe and the thirteenth-largest container port in the world.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Athens metropolitan area extends beyond its administrative municipal city limits as well as its urban agglomeration, with a population of 3,638,281 in 2021 over an area of 2,928.717 km2 (1,131 sq mi).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The heritage of the Classical Era is still evident in the city, represented by ancient monuments, and works of art, the most famous of these being the Parthenon, considered a key landmark of early Western culture.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens retains Roman, Byzantine and a smaller number of Ottoman monuments, while its historical urban core features elements of continuity through its millennia of history.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens contains two World Heritage Sites recognised by UNESCO: the Acropolis of Athens and the medieval Daphni Monastery.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens is home to several museums and cultural institutions, such as the National Archeological Museum, featuring the world's largest collection of ancient Greek antiquities, the Acropolis Museum, the Museum of Cycladic Art, the Benaki Museum and the Byzantine and Christian Museum.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens was the host city of the first modern-day Olympic Games in 1896, and 108 years later it hosted the 2004 Summer Olympics, making it one of five cities to have hosted the Summer Olympics on more than one occasion.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In Ancient Greek, the city's name was Ἀθῆναι (*Athênai*, pronounced [atʰɛ̂ːnai̯] in Classical Attic), which is a plural word.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In earlier Greek, such as Homeric Greek, the name had been current in the singular form though, as Ἀθήνη (*Athḗnē*).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It was possibly rendered in the plural later on, like those of Θῆβαι (*Thêbai*) and Μυκῆναι (*Μukênai*).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The root of the word is probably not of Greek or Indo-European origin, and is possibly a remnant of the Pre-Greek substrate of Attica.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In classical antiquity it was debated whether Athens took its name from its patron goddess Athena (Attic Ἀθηνᾶ, *Athēnâ*, Ionic Ἀθήνη, *Athḗnē*, and Doric Ἀθάνα, *Athā́nā*) or Athena took her name from the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Modern scholars now generally agree that the goddess takes her name from the city, because the ending -*ene* is common in names of locations, but rare for personal names.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] According to the account given by Pseudo-Apollodorus, Poseidon struck the ground with his trident and a salt water spring welled up.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In an alternative version of the myth from Virgil's poem *Georgics*, Poseidon instead gave the Athenians the first horse.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In both versions, Athena offered the Athenians the first domesticated olive tree.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Cecrops accepted this gift and declared Athena the patron goddess of Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Eight different etymologies, now commonly rejected, have been proposed since the 17th century.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Christian Lobeck proposed as the root of the name the word ἄθος (*áthos*) or ἄνθος (*ánthos*) meaning "flower", to denote Athens as the "flowering city".
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Ludwig von Döderlein proposed the stem of the verb θάω, stem θη- (*tháō*, *thē-*, "to suck") to denote Athens as having fertile soil.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athenians were called cicada-wearers (Ancient Greek: Τεττιγοφόροι) because they used to wear pins of golden cicadas.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] A symbol of being autochthonous (earth-born), because the legendary founder of Athens, Erechtheus was an autochthon or of being musicians, because the cicada is a "musician" insect.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In classical literature the city was sometimes referred to as the City of the Violet Crown, first documented in Pindar's ἰοστέφανοι Ἀθᾶναι (*iostéphanoi Athânai*), or as τὸ κλεινὸν ἄστυ (*tò kleinòn ásty*, "the glorious city").
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] During the medieval period, the name of the city was rendered once again in the singular as Ἀθήνα.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Variant names included Setines, Satine, and Astines, all derivations involving false splitting of prepositional phrases.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] King Alphonse X of Castile credits Ovid with the false etymology 'the place without death' because of Athens' arts and sciences "that never die".
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In Ottoman Turkish, it was called آتينا‎ *Ātīnā*.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The oldest known human presence in Athens is the Cave of Schist, which has been dated to between the 11th and 7th millennia BC.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens has been continuously inhabited for at least 5,000 years (3000 BC).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] By 1400 BC, the settlement had become an important centre of the Mycenaean civilisation, and the Acropolis was the site of a major Mycenaean fortress, whose remains can be recognised from sections of the characteristic Cyclopean walls.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Unlike other Mycenaean centres, such as Mycenae and Pylos, it is not known whether Athens suffered destruction in about 1200 BC, an event often attributed to a Dorian invasion, and the Athenians always maintained that they were pure Ionians with no Dorian element.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] However, Athens, like many other Bronze Age settlements, went into economic decline for around 150 years afterwards.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Iron Age burials, in the Kerameikos and other locations, are often richly provided for and demonstrate that from 900 BC onwards Athens was one of the leading centres of trade and prosperity in the region.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] By the sixth century BC, widespread social unrest led to the reforms of Solon.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] These would pave the way for the eventual introduction of democracy by Cleisthenes in 508 BC.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens had by this time become a significant naval power with a large fleet, and helped the rebellion of the Ionian cities against Persian rule.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] However, this did not prevent Athens from being captured and sacked twice by the Persians within one year, after a heroic but ultimately failed resistance at Thermopylae by Spartans and other Greeks led by King Leonidas, after both Boeotia and Attica fell to the Persians.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The decades that followed became known as the Golden Age of the Athenian democracy, during which time Athens became the leading city of Ancient Greece, with its cultural achievements laying the foundations for Western civilisation.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The playwrights Aeschylus, Sophocles and Euripides flourished in Athens during this time, as did the historians Herodotus and Thucydides, the physician Hippocrates, and the philosophers Socrates and Plato.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Guided by Pericles, who promoted the arts and fostered democracy, Athens embarked on an ambitious building program that saw the construction of the Acropolis of Athens (including the Parthenon), as well as empire-building via the Delian League.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Originally intended as an association of Greek city-states, which were led by Cimon, to continue the fight against the Persians, the league soon turned into a vehicle for Athens's own imperial ambitions.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The resulting tensions brought about the Peloponnesian War (431–404 BC), in which Athens was defeated by its rival Sparta.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Nonetheless the city reemerged soon as a major power in the Greek world, forming the Second Athenian League during the time of the Spartan and Theban hegemonies.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] By the mid-4th century BC the northern Greek kingdom of Macedon was becoming dominant in Greek affairs.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In 338 BC the armies of Philip II and his son Alexander the Great defeated an alliance of some of the Greek city-states led by Athens and Thebes at the Battle of Chaeronea.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] After this defeat, Athens joined the Hellenic League under Philip and then Alexander.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Later, under Rome, Athens was given the status of a free city because of its widely admired schools.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the second century AD, the Roman emperor Hadrian, himself an Athenian citizen, ordered the construction of a number of public buildings.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Paul the Apostle visited Athens on his second missionary journey.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens was sacked in 267 AD by a Germanic tribe.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the early 4th century AD the Eastern Roman Empire began to be governed from Constantinople, and with the construction and expansion of the imperial city, many of Athens's works of art were taken by the emperors to adorn it.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Empire became Christianised, and the use of Latin declined in favour of exclusive use of Greek; in the Roman imperial period, both languages had been used.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the later Roman period, Athens was ruled by the emperors continuing until the 13th century, its citizens identifying themselves as citizens of the Roman Empire ("*Rhomaioi*").
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The conversion of the empire from paganism to Christianity greatly affected Athens, resulting in reduced reverence for the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Ancient monuments such as the Parthenon, Erechtheion and the Hephaisteion (Theseion) were converted into churches.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] As the empire became increasingly anti-pagan, Athens became a provincial town and experienced fluctuating fortunes.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The city remained an important centre of learning, especially of Neoplatonism—with notable pupils including Gregory of Nazianzus, Basil of Caesarea and the Roman emperor Julian (r.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] 355–363)—and consequently a centre of paganism.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Christian items do not appear in the archaeological record until the early 5th century.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The sack of the city by the Herules in 267 and by the Visigoths under their king Alaric I (r.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] 395–410) in 396, however, dealt a heavy blow to the city's fabric and fortunes, and Athens was henceforth confined to a small fortified area that embraced a fraction of the ancient city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] 527–565) banned the teaching of philosophy by pagans in 529, an event whose impact on the city is much debated, but is generally taken to mark the end of the ancient history of Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens was sacked by the Slavs in 582, but remained in imperial hands thereafter, as highlighted by the visit of the emperor Constans II (r.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] 641–668) in 662/3 and its inclusion in the Theme of Hellas.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the great dispute over Byzantine Iconoclasm, Athens is commonly held to have supported the iconophile position, chiefly due to the role played by Empress Irene of Athens in the ending of the first period of Iconoclasm at the Second Council of Nicaea in 787.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] A few years later, another Athenian, Theophano, became empress as the wife of Staurakios (r.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Invasion of the empire by the Turks after the Battle of Manzikert in 1071, and the ensuing civil wars, largely passed the region by and Athens continued its provincial existence unharmed.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] When the Byzantine Empire was rescued by the resolute leadership of the three Komnenos emperors Alexios, John and Manuel, Attica and the rest of Greece prospered.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Archaeological evidence tells us that the medieval town experienced a period of rapid and sustained growth, starting in the 11th century and continuing until the end of the 12th century.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Agora (marketplace) had been deserted since late antiquity, began to be built over, and soon the town became an important centre for the production of soaps and dyes.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The growth of the town attracted the Venetians, and various other traders who frequented the ports of the Aegean, to Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] This interest in trade appears to have further increased the economic prosperity of the town.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The 11th and 12th centuries were the Golden Age of Byzantine art in Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Almost all of the most important Middle Byzantine churches in and around Athens were built during these two centuries, and this reflects the growth of the town in general.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In 1204, the Fourth Crusade conquered Athens and the city was not recovered from the Latins before it was taken by the Ottoman Turks.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It did not become Greek in government again until the 19th century.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] From 1204 until 1458, Athens was ruled by Latins in three separate periods, following the Crusades.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The "Latins", or "Franks", were western Europeans and followers of the Latin Church brought to the Eastern Mediterranean during the Crusades.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Along with rest of Byzantine Greece, Athens was part of the series of feudal fiefs, similar to the Crusader states established in Syria and on Cyprus after the First Crusade.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] This period is known as the *Frankokratia*.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The first Ottoman attack on Athens, which involved a short-lived occupation of the town, came in 1397, under the Ottoman generals Yaqub Pasha and Timurtash.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In 1458, Athens was captured by the Ottomans under the personal leadership of Sultan Mehmed II.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] As the Ottoman Sultan rode into the city, he was greatly struck by the beauty of its ancient monuments and issued a *firman* (imperial edict) forbidding their looting or destruction, on pain of death.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Parthenon was converted into the main mosque of the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Under Ottoman rule, Athens was denuded of any importance and its population severely declined, leaving it as a "small country town" (Franz Babinger).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] From the early 17th century, Athens came under the jurisdiction of the Kizlar Agha, the chief black eunuch of the Sultan's harem.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The city had originally been granted by Sultan Ahmed I (r.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] 1603–1617) to Basilica, one of his favourite concubines, who hailed from the city, in response of complaints of maladministration by the local governors.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] After her death, Athens came under the purview of the Kizlar Agha.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Turks began a practice of storing gunpowder and explosives in the Parthenon and Propylaea.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In 1640, a lightning bolt struck the Propylaea, causing its destruction.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In 1687, during the Morean War, the Acropolis was besieged by the Venetians under Francesco Morosini, and the temple of Athena Nike was dismantled by the Ottomans to fortify the Parthenon.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] A shot fired during the bombardment of the Acropolis caused a powder magazine in the Parthenon to explode (26 September), and the building was severely damaged, giving it largely the appearance it has today.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Venetian occupation of Athens lasted for six months, and both the Venetians and the Ottomans participated in the looting of the Parthenon.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] One of its western pediments was removed, causing even more damage to the structure.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] During the Venetian occupation, the two mosques of the city were converted into Catholic and Protestant churches, but on 9 April 1688 the Venetians abandoned Athens again to the Ottomans.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In 1822, a Greek insurgency captured the city, but it fell to the Ottomans again in 1826, although the Acropolis held till June 1827.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Again the ancient monuments suffered badly.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Ottoman forces remained in possession until March 1833, when they withdrew.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Following the Greek War of Independence and the establishment of the Greek Kingdom, Athens was chosen to replace Nafplio as the second capital of the newly independent Greek state in 1834, largely because of historical and sentimental reasons.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] At the time, after the extensive destruction it had suffered during the war of independence, it was reduced to a town of about 4,000 people (less than half its earlier population) in a loose swarm of houses along the foot of the Acropolis.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The first King of Greece, King Otto of Bavaria, commissioned the architects Stamatios Kleanthis and Eduard Schaubert to design a modern city plan fit for the capital of a state.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The first modern city plan consisted of a triangle defined by the Acropolis, the ancient cemetery of Kerameikos and the new palace of the Bavarian king (now housing the Greek Parliament), so as to highlight the continuity between modern and ancient Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Neoclassicism, the international style of this epoch, was the architectural style through which Bavarian, French and Greek architects such as Hansen, Klenze, Boulanger or Kaftantzoglou designed the first important public buildings of the new capital.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In 1896, Athens hosted the first modern Olympic Games.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the 1920s a number of Greek refugees, expelled from Asia Minor after the Greco-Turkish War and Population exchange between Greece and Turkey, swelled Athens's population.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens was occupied by the Axis (primarily German soldiers) during World War II and experienced terrible privations during the later years of the war.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Great Famine greatly affected the city during the occupation.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Several resistance organizations were present inside Athens to fight against the occupation, with EAM being the main movement of the Greek Resistance.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Following the liberation of Greece from the Axis powers, Dekemvriana rocked the city with heavy fighting between communist forces and government forces backed by the British.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] After the Civil War ended, Athen's population boomed in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the 1980s it became evident that smog from factories and an ever-increasing fleet of cars, as well as a lack of adequate free space due to congestion, had evolved into the city's most important challenge.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Further urban improvements began in the 2020s along the coastal zone, including the Hellenikon Park development and the Faliro Delta upgrade, adding to the Stavros Niarchos Centre.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Hellenikon Park development will feature the Hard Rock Hotel & Casino Athens, the first integrated resort in continental Europe and the Riviera Tower.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens sprawls across the central plain of Attica that is often referred to as the **Athens Basin** or the **Attica Basin** (Greek: Λεκανοπέδιο Αθηνών/Αττικής, romanised: *Lekanopédio Athinón/Attikís*).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The basin is bounded by four large mountains: Mount Aigaleo to the west, Mount Parnitha to the north, Mount Pentelicus to the northeast and Mount Hymettus to the east.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Beyond Mount Aegaleo lies the Thriasian plain, which forms an extension of the central plain to the west.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Mount Parnitha is the tallest of the four mountains (1,413 metres or 4,636 feet), and has been declared a national park.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Athens urban area spreads over 50 kilometres (31 mi) from Agios Stefanos in the north to Varkiza in the south.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The city is located in the north temperate zone, 38 degrees north of the equator.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens is built around a large number of hills.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Lycabettus is one of the tallest hills of the city proper and provides a view of the entire Attica Basin.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The meteorology of Athens is deemed to be one of the most complex in the world because its mountains cause a temperature inversion phenomenon which, along with the Greek government's difficulties controlling industrial pollution, was responsible for the air pollution problems the city has faced.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] This issue is not unique to Athens; for instance, Los Angeles and Mexico City also suffer from similar atmospheric inversion problems.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Cephissus river, the Ilisos and the Eridanos stream are the historical rivers of Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Measures taken by the Greek authorities throughout the 1990s have improved the quality of air over the Attica Basin.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Nevertheless, air pollution still remains an issue for Athens, particularly during the hottest summer days.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In late June 2007, the Attica region experienced a number of brush fires, including a blaze that burned a significant portion of a large forested national park in Mount Parnitha, considered critical to maintaining a better air quality in Athens all year round.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Damage to the park has led to worries over a stalling in the improvement of air quality in the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The major waste management efforts undertaken in the last decade, particularly the plant built on the small island of Psytalia, have greatly improved water quality in the Saronic Gulf, and the coastal waters of Athens are now accessible again to swimmers.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Parnitha National Park is punctuated by well-marked paths, gorges, springs, torrents and caves dotting the protected area.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Hiking and mountain-biking in all four mountains are popular outdoor activities for residents of the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The National Garden of Athens was completed in 1840 and is a green refuge of 15.5 hectares in the centre of the Greek capital.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Located between the Parliament and Zappeion buildings, the latter of which maintains its own garden of seven hectares.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Parts of the City Centre have been redeveloped under a masterplan called the *Unification of Archeological Sites of Athens*, which has also gathered funding from the EU to help enhance the project.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The landmark Dionysiou Areopagitou Street has been pedestrianised, forming a scenic route.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The route starts from the Temple of Olympian Zeus at Vasilissis Olgas Avenue, continues under the southern slopes of the Acropolis near Plaka, and finishes just beyond the Temple of Hephaestus in Thiseio.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The route in its entirety provides visitors with views of the Parthenon and the Agora, the meeting point of ancient Athenians, away from the busy City Centre.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The hills of Athens also provide green space.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Lycabettus, Philopappos hill and the area around it, including Pnyx and Ardettos hill, are planted with pines and other trees, with the character of a small forest rather than typical metropolitan parkland.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Also to be found is the Pedion tou Areos (*Field of Mars*) of 27.7 hectares, near the National Archaeological Museum.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (Köppen climate classification: *Csa*).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Especially during summer the climate in Athens can be considered warmer than some cities that are similar or even closer to the Equator such as Seoul, Melbourne, Buenos Aires and Cape Town.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Fog is rare in the city centre, but somewhat more frequent in areas to the east, close to Mt.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Advection fog can occur in spring, especially along the coastline.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The southern section of the Athens metropolitan area (i.e., Elliniko) lies in the transitional zone between Mediterranean (*Csa*) and hot semi-arid climate (*BSh*), with its port-city of Piraeus being the most extreme example, receiving just 331.9 millimetres (13.07 in) per year.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The areas to the south generally see less extreme temperature variations as their climate is moderated by the Saronic gulf.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Kifissia), owing to its higher elevation, features moderately lower temperatures and slightly increased precipitation year-round.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The generally dry climate of the Athens basin compared to the precipitation amounts seen in a typical Mediterranean climate is due to the rain shadow effect caused by the Pindus mountain range and the Dirfys and Parnitha mountains, substantially drying the westerly and northerly winds respectively.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It usually does not cause heavy disruption to daily life, in contrast to the northern parts of the city, where blizzards occur on a more regular basis.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The most recent examples include the snowstorms of 16 February 2021 and 24 January 2022, when the entire urban area was blanketed in snow, apart, in the second case, to some areas adjacent to Piraeus.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens may get particularly hot in the summer, owing partly to the strong urban heat island effect characterising the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In fact, Athens has been referred to as the hottest city in mainland Europe, and is the first city in Europe to appoint a chief heat officer to deal with severe heat waves.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Temperatures of 47.5°C and over have been reported in several locations of the metropolitan area, including within the urban agglomeration.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Elefsina, to the west of the city, was until 2021 the holder of the World Meteorological Organization record for the highest temperature recorded in Europe with 48.0 °C (118.4 °F) which was recorded on 10 July 1977.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens became the capital of Greece in 1834, following Nafplion, which was the provisional capital from 1829.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The municipality (city) of Athens is also the capital of the Attica region.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The term *Athens* can refer either to the municipality of Athens, to Greater Athens or urban area, or to the entire Athens Metropolitan Area.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The seven **municipal communities** are only named by numbers.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Athens urban area spans over 412 km2 (159 sq mi), with a population of 3,059,764 people as of 2021.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens and Piraeus municipalities serve as the two metropolitan centres of the Athens Metropolitan Area.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] There are also some inter-municipal centres serving specific areas.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] For example, Kifissia and Glyfada serve as inter-municipal centres for northern and southern suburbs respectively.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Athens Metropolitan Area consists of 58 densely populated municipalities, sprawling around the Municipality of Athens (the City Centre) in virtually all directions.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] For the Athenians, all the urban municipalities surrounding the City Centre are called suburbs.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Athens city coastline, extending from the major commercial port of Piraeus to the southernmost suburb of Varkiza for some 25 km (20 mi), is also connected to the City Centre by tram.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the northern suburb of Maroussi, the upgraded main Olympic Complex (known by its Greek acronym OAKA) dominates the skyline.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The area has been redeveloped according to a design by the Spanish architect Santiago Calatrava, with steel arches, landscaped gardens, fountains, futuristic glass, and a landmark new blue glass roof which was added to the main stadium.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] A second Olympic complex, next to the sea at the beach of Palaio Faliro, also features modern stadia, shops and an elevated esplanade.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Work is underway to transform the grounds of the old Athens Airport – named Elliniko – in the southern suburbs, into one of the largest landscaped parks in Europe, to be named the Hellenikon Metropolitan Park.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Many of the southern suburbs (such as Alimos, Palaio Faliro, Elliniko, Glyfada, Voula, Vouliagmeni and Varkiza) known as the Athens Riviera, host a number of sandy beaches, most of which are operated by the Greek National Tourism Organisation and require an entrance fee.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Casinos operate on both Mount Parnitha (Regency Casino Mont Parnes), some 25 km (16 mi) from downtown Athens (accessible by car or cable car), and the nearby town of Loutraki (accessible by car via the EO8, EO8a then A8, or the Athens Suburban Railway).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The concept of a partner city is used under different names in different countries, but they mean the same thing, that two cities in different countries assist each other as partners.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Municipality of Athens had a population of 643,452 people in 2021.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In the 2021 Population and Housing Census, the four regional units that make up the former Athens prefecture have a combined population of 2,611,713.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] They, together with the regional unit of Piraeus (sometimes referred to as Greater Piraeus) make up the dense Athens Urban Area, or Greater Athens, which reaches a total population of 3,059,764 inhabitants (in 2021).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The municipality (centre) of Athens is the most populous in Greece, with a population of 643,452 people (in 2021) and an area of 38.96 km2 (15.04 sq mi), forming the core of the Athens Urban Area within the Attica Basin.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The incumbent Mayor of Athens is Charis Doukas of PASOK.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The municipality is divided into seven municipal districts which are mainly used for administrative purposes.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] For the Athenians the most popular way of dividing the downtown is through its neighbourhoods such as Pagkrati, Ampelokipoi, Goudi, Exarcheia, Patisia, Ilisia, Petralona, Plaka, Anafiotika, Koukaki, Kolonaki and Kypseli, each with its own distinct history and characteristics.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Romani people are concentrated in Acharnes, Ano Liosia, Agia Varvara, Zefeiri and Kamatero.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] There is a large Albanian community in Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Athens Metropolitan Area, with an area of 2,928.717 km2 (1,131 sq mi) and inhabited by 3,744,059 people in 2021, consists of the Athens Urban Area with the addition of the towns and villages of East and West Attica, which surround the dense urban area of the Greek capital.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It actually sprawls over the whole peninsula of Attica, which is the best part of the region of Attica, excluding the islands.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens ranks in the lowest percentage for the risk on frequency and severity of terrorist attacks according to the EU Global Terrorism Database (EIU 2007–2016 calculations).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The city also ranked 35th in Digital Security, 21st on Health Security, 29th on Infrastructure Security and 41st on Personal Security globally in a 2017 The Economist Intelligence Unit report.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] It also ranks as a very safe city (39th globally out of 162 cities overall) on the ranking of the safest and most dangerous countries.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] As November 2024 the crime index from Numbeo places Athens at 55.40 (moderate), while its safety index is at 44.60.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] According to a Mercer 2019 Quality of Living Survey, Athens ranks 89th on the Mercer Quality of Living Survey ranking.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens is the financial capital of Greece.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] According to data from 2014, Athens as a metropolitan economic area produced US$130 billion as GDP in PPP, which consists of nearly half of the production for the whole country.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens was ranked 102nd in that year's list of global economic metropolises, while GDP per capita for the same year was 32,000 US dollars.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens is one of the major economic centres in south-eastern Europe and is considered a regional economic power.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Prominent Greek companies such as Hellas Sat, Hellenic Aerospace Industry, Mytilineos Holdings, Titan Cement, Hellenic Petroleum, Papadopoulos E.J., Folli Follie, Jumbo S.A., OPAP, and Cosmote have their headquarters in the metropolitan area of Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Multinational companies such as Ericsson, Sony, Siemens, Motorola, Samsung, Microsoft, Teleperformance, Novartis, Mondelez and Coca-Cola also have their regional research and development headquarters in the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The banking sector is represented by National Bank of Greece, Alpha Bank, Eurobank, and Piraeus Bank, while the Bank of Greece is also situated in the City Centre.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Athens Stock Exchange was severely hit by the Greek government-debt crisis and the decision of the government to proceed into capital controls during summer 2015.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] As a whole the economy of Athens and Greece was strongly affected, while data showed a change from long recession to growth of 1.4% from 2017 onwards.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Tourism is also a leading contributor to the economy of the city, as one of Europe's top destinations for city-break tourism, and also the gateway for excursions to both the islands and other parts of the mainland.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Greece attracted 26.5 million visitors in 2015, 30.1 million visitors in 2017, and over 33 million in 2018, making Greece one of the most visited countries in Europe and the world, and contributing 18% to the country's GDP.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens welcomed more than 5 million tourists in 2018, and 1.4 million were "city-breakers"; this was an increase by over a million city-breakers since 2013.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Athens has been a destination for travellers since antiquity.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] Over the 2000s, the city's infrastructure and social amenities have improved, in part because of its successful bid to stage the 2004 Olympic Games.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] The Greek Government, aided by the EU, has funded major infrastructure projects such as the state-of-the-art Eleftherios Venizelos International Airport, the expansion of the Athens Metro system, and the new Attiki Odos Motorway.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p01] In recent years, Athens has become more dynamic with the addition of numerous new bars and cafés and a growing presence of street art and graffiti, enhancing its urban edge and adding more tourist options alongside the city's archaeological sites and museums.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens is the country's major transportation hub.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The city has Greece's largest airport and its largest port; Piraeus, too, is the largest container transport port in the Mediterranean, and the largest passenger port in Europe.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens is a major national hub for Intercity (Ktel) and international buses, as well as for domestic and international rail transport.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Public transport is serviced by a variety of transportation means, making up the country's largest mass transit system.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Transport for Athens operates a large bus and trolleybus fleet, the city's Metro and a tram network, connecting the southern suburbs to the city centre.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Hellenic Train operates Suburban Railway services.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] OSY (Greek: ΟΣΥ) (Odikes Sygkoinonies S.A.), a subsidiary company of OASA (Athens urban transport organisation), is the main operator of buses and trolleybuses in Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] As of 2017, its network consists of around 322 bus lines, spanning the Athens Metropolitan Area, and making up a fleet of 2,375 buses and trolleybuses.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Of those 2,375, 619 buses run on compressed natural gas, making up the largest fleet of natural gas-powered buses in Europe, and 354 are electric-powered (trolleybuses).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] All of the 354 trolleybuses are equipped to run on diesel in case of power failure.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] International links are provided by a number of private companies.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] National and regional bus links are provided by KTEL from two InterCity Bus Terminals; Kifissos Bus Terminal A and Liosion Bus Terminal B, both located in the north-western part of the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] *Kifissos* provides connections towards Peloponnese, North Greece, West Greece and some Ionian Islands, whereas *Liosion* is used for most of Central Greece.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Both of these terminals will be replaced by a new Intercity Bus Terminal under construction in Eleonas due to be completed by 2027.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens is the hub of the country's national railway system (OSE), connecting the capital with major cities across Greece and abroad (Istanbul, Sofia, Belgrade and Bucharest).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Athens Suburban Railway, referred to as the *Proastiakos*, connects Athens International Airport to the city of Kiato, 106 km (66 mi) west of Athens, via Larissa station, the city's central rail station and the port of Piraeus.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The length of Athens's commuter rail network extends to 120 km (75 mi), and is expected to stretch to 281 km (175 mi) by 2010.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Athens Metro is operated by STASY S.A.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] (Greek: ΣΤΑΣΥ) (Statheres Sygkoinonies S.A.), a subsidiary company of OASA (Athens urban transport organisation), which provides public transport throughout the Athens Urban Area.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] While its main purpose is transport, it also houses Greek artefacts found during the construction of the system.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Athens Metro runs three metro lines, namely Line 1 (Green Line), Line 2 (Red Line) and Line 3 (Blue Line) lines, of which the first was constructed in 1869, and the other two largely during the 1990s, with the initial new sections opened in January 2000.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Line 1 mostly runs at ground level and the other two (Line 2 & 3) routes run entirely underground.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] A fleet of 42 trains, using 252 carriages, operates on the network, with a daily occupancy of 1,353,000 passengers.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Athens Tram is operated by STASY S.A.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] (Statheres Sygkoinonies S.A.), a subsidiary company of Transport for Athens (OASA).
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] It has a fleet of 35 Sirio type vehicles and 25 Alstom Citadis type vehicles which serve 48 stations, employ 345 people with an average daily occupancy of 65,000 passengers.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The tram network spans a total length of 27 km (17 mi) and covers ten Athenian suburbs.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The network runs from Syntagma Square to the southwestern suburb of Palaio Faliro, where the line splits in two branches; the first runs along the Athens coastline toward the southern suburb of Voula, while the other heads toward Piraeus.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The network covers the majority of the Athens coastline.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens is served by the Athens International Airport (ATH), located near the town of Spata, in the eastern Messoghia plain, some 35 km (22 mi) east of the centre of Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The airport, awarded the "European Airport of the Year 2004" Award, is intended as an expandable hub for air travel in southeastern Europe and was constructed in 51 months, costing 2.2 billion euros.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Port of Piraeus is the largest port in Greece and one of the largest in Europe.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Rafina and Lavrio act as alternative ports of Athens, connects the city with numerous Greek islands of the Aegean Sea, Evia while also serving the cruise ships that arrive.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Two main motorways of Greece begin in Athens, namely the A1/E75, heading north towards Greece's second largest city, Thessaloniki and the border crossing of Evzonoi; and the A8/E94 heading west, towards Greece's third largest city, Patras, which incorporated the EO8a national road.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Before their completion, much of the road traffic used the EO1 and EO8 roads.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The span of the Attiki Odos in all its length is 65 km (40 mi), making it the largest metropolitan motorway network in all of Greece.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Located on Panepistimiou Street, the old campus of the University of Athens, the National Library, and the Athens Academy form the "Athens Trilogy" built in the mid-19th century.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The largest and oldest university in Athens is the National and Kapodistrian University of Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Most of the functions of NKUA along National Technical University of Athens have been transferred to a campus in the eastern suburb of Zografou.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The National Technical University of Athens old campus is located on Patision Street.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The University of West Attica is the second largest university in Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The seat of the university is located in the western area of Athens, where the philosophers of Ancient Athens delivered lectures.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] All the activities of UNIWA are carried out in the modern infrastructure of the three University Campuses within the metropolitan region of Athens (Egaleo Park, Ancient Olive Groove and Athens), which offer modern teaching and research spaces, entertainment and support facilities for all students.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Other universities that lie within Athens are the Athens University of Economics and Business, the Panteion University, the Agricultural University of Athens and the University of Piraeus.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] There are also several other private *colleges*, as they called formally in Greece, as the establishment of private universities is prohibited by the constitution.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Many of them are accredited by a foreign state or university such as the American College of Greece and the Athens Campus of the University of Indianapolis.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The city is a world centre of archaeological research.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The city is also the setting for the Demokritos laboratory for Archaeometry, alongside regional and national archaeological authorities forming part of the Greek Department of Culture.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens hosts 17 Foreign Archaeological Institutes which promote and facilitate research by scholars from their home countries.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] As a result, Athens has more than a dozen archaeological libraries and three specialised archaeological laboratories, and is the venue of several hundred specialised lectures, conferences and seminars, as well as dozens of archaeological exhibitions each year.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] At any given time, hundreds of international scholars and researchers in all disciplines of archaeology are to be found in the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens incorporates architectural styles ranging from Greco-Roman and Neoclassical to Modern.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] They are often to be found in the same areas, as Athens is not marked by a uniformity of architectural style.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] A visitor will quickly notice the absence of tall buildings: Athens has very strict height restriction laws in order to ensure the Acropolis Hill is visible throughout the city.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Despite the variety in styles, there is evidence of continuity in elements of the architectural environment throughout the city's history.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] For the greatest part of the 19th century Neoclassicism dominated Athens, as well as some deviations from it such as Eclecticism, especially in the early 20th century.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Thus, the Old Royal Palace was the first important public building to be built, between 1836 and 1843.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Later in the mid and late 19th century, Theophil Freiherr von Hansen and Ernst Ziller took part in the construction of many neoclassical buildings such as the Athens Academy and the Zappeion Hall.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Ziller also designed many private mansions in the centre of Athens which gradually became public, usually through donations, such as Schliemann's Iliou Melathron.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Beginning in the 1920s, modern architecture including Bauhaus and Art Deco began to exert an influence on almost all Greek architects, and buildings both public and private were constructed in accordance with these styles.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Localities with a great number of such buildings include Kolonaki, and some areas of the centre of the city; neighbourhoods developed in this period include Kypseli.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] In the 1950s and 1960s during the extension and development of Athens, other modern movements such as the International style played an important role.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The centre of Athens was largely rebuilt, leading to the demolition of a number of neoclassical buildings.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The architects of this era employed materials such as glass, marble and aluminium, and many blended modern and classical elements.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] After World War II, internationally known architects to have designed and built in the city included Walter Gropius, with his design for the US Embassy, and, among others, Eero Saarinen, in his postwar design for the east terminal of the Ellinikon Airport.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Across the city numerous statues or busts are to be found.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] A significant landmark is also the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier in Syntagma.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens is home to 148 theatrical stages, more than any other city in the world, including the ancient Odeon of Herodes Atticus, home to the Athens Festival, which runs from May to October each year.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] In addition to a large number of multiplexes, Athens plays host to open air garden cinemas.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The city also supports music venues, including the Athens Concert Hall (*Megaro Moussikis*), which attracts world class artists.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Athens Planetarium, located in Andrea Syngrou Avenue, in Palaio Faliro is one of the largest and best equipped digital planetaria in the world.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Stavros Niarchos Foundation Cultural Center, inaugurated in 2016, will house the National Library of Greece and the Greek National Opera.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] In 2018 Athens was designated as the World Book Capital by UNESCO.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The coastal suburbs of Microlimano, Alimos and Glyfada include many tavernas, beach bars and busy summer clubs.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] In 1922, following the Greek-Turkish war, Greek genocide and later population exchange suffered by the Greek population of Asia Minor, many ethnic Greeks fled to Athens.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] They settled in poor neighbourhoods and brought with them Rebetiko music, making it also popular in Greece, and which later became the base for the Laïko music.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Other forms of song popular today in Greece are elafrolaika, entechno, dimotika, and skyladika.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Greece's most notable, and internationally famous, composers of Greek song, mainly of the entechno form, are Manos Hadjidakis and Mikis Theodorakis.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Both composers have achieved fame abroad for their composition of film scores.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The renowned American-born Greek soprano Maria Callas spent her teenage years in Athens, where she settled in 1937.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Her professional opera career started in 1940 in Athens, with the Greek National Opera.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] In 2018, the city's municipal Olympia Theatre was renamed the "Olympia City Music Theatre 'Maria Callas'" and in 2023, the Municipality inaugurated the Maria Callas Museum, housing it in a neoclassical building on 44 Mitropoleos street.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens has a long tradition in sports and sporting events, serving as home to the most important clubs in Greek sport and housing a large number of sports facilities.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The city has also been host to sports events of international importance.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens has hosted the Summer Olympic Games twice, in 1896 and 2004.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The 2004 Summer Olympics required the development of the Athens Olympic Stadium, which has since gained a reputation as one of the most beautiful stadiums in the world, and one of its most interesting modern monuments.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The biggest stadium in the country, it hosted two finals of the UEFA Champions League, in 1994 and 2007.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Other major stadiums are the Karaiskakis Stadium located in the nearby city of Piraeus, a sports and entertainment complex, host of the 1971 UEFA Cup Winners' Cup Final, and Agia Sophia Stadium located in Nea Filadelfeia, host of the 2024 UEFA Europa Conference League final.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The EuroLeague final has been hosted twice in 1985 and in 1993 at the Peace and Friendship Stadium, most known as SEF, a large indoor arena, and the third time in 2007 at the Olympic Indoor Hall.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Events in other sports such as athletics, volleyball, water polo etc., have been hosted in the capital's venues.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Greater Athens is home to three widely supported and successful multi-sport clubs, Panathinaikos, originated in the city of Athens, Olympiacos, originated in the port city of Piraeus and AEK, originated in the suburban town of Nea Filadelfeia.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] In football, Olympiacos is the dominant force at the national level and the only Greek club to have won a European competition, the 2023–24 UEFA Europa Conference League, Panathinaikos made it to the 1971 European Cup Final, while AEK Athens is the other member of the big three.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] These clubs also have successful basketball teams; Panathinaikos and Olympiacos are considered among the top powers in Europe, having won the EuroLeague seven and three times respectively, whilst AEK Athens was the first Greek team to win a European trophy in any team sport.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Other notable clubs within the region are Athinaikos, Panionios, Atromitos, Apollon Smyrnis, Panellinios, Egaleo, Ethinkos Piraeus, Maroussi BC and Peristeri B.C.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athenian clubs have also had domestic and international success in other sports.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The Athens area encompasses a variety of terrain, notably hills and mountains rising around the city, and the capital is the only major city in Europe to be bisected by a mountain range.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Four mountain ranges extend into city boundaries and thousands of kilometres of trails criss-cross the city and neighbouring areas, providing exercise and wilderness access on foot and on bicycle.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Beyond Athens and across the prefecture of Attica, outdoor activities include skiing, rock climbing, hang gliding and windsurfing.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Numerous outdoor clubs serve these sports, including the Athens Chapter of the Sierra Club, which leads over 4,000 outings annually in the area.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Athens was awarded the 2004 Summer Olympics on 5 September 1997 in Lausanne, Switzerland, after having lost a previous bid to host the 1996 Summer Olympics, to Atlanta, United States.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] It was to be the second time Athens would host the games, following the inaugural event of 1896.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] After an unsuccessful bid in 1990, the 1997 bid was radically improved, including an appeal to Greece's Olympic history.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] In the last round of voting, Athens defeated Rome with 66 votes to 41.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Prior to this round, the cities of Buenos Aires, Stockholm and Cape Town had been eliminated from competition, having received fewer votes.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Although the heavy cost was criticised, estimated at US$1.5 billion, Athens was transformed into a more functional city that enjoys modern technology both in transportation and in modern urban development.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The games welcomed over 10,000 athletes from 202 countries.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The municipality of Athens is divided in 58 electoral precincts.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] The current precinct limits were instated beginning with the 2004 election in order for the precincts to have a roughly equal electorate.
[src:aeolipile/athens-p02] Before 2004 there were 68 precincts, the limits of which corresponded to the Orthodox Parishes of Athens.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] A **bearing** is a machine element that constrains relative motion to only the desired motion and reduces friction between moving parts.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The design of the bearing may, for example, provide for free linear movement of the moving part or for free rotation around a fixed axis; or, it may prevent a motion by controlling the vectors of normal forces that bear on the moving parts.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Most bearings facilitate the desired motion by minimizing friction.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearings are classified broadly according to the type of operation, the motions allowed, or the directions of the loads (forces) applied to the parts.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The term "bearing" is derived from the verb "to bear"; a bearing being a machine element that allows one part to bear (i.e., to support) another.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The simplest bearings are bearing surfaces, cut or formed into a part, with varying degrees of control over the form, size, roughness, and location of the surface.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Other bearings are separate devices installed into a machine or machine part.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The most sophisticated bearings for the most demanding applications are very precise components; their manufacture requires some of the highest standards of current technology.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Rotary bearings hold rotating components such as shafts or axles within mechanical systems and transfer axial and radial loads from the source of the load to the structure supporting it.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The simplest form of bearing, the *plain bearing*, consists of a shaft rotating in a hole.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Lubricants come in different forms, including liquids, solids, and gases.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The choice of lubricant depends on the specific application and factors such as temperature, load, and speed.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In the *ball bearing* and *roller bearing*, to reduce sliding friction, rolling elements such as rollers or balls with a circular cross-section are located between the races or journals of the bearing assembly.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] A wide variety of bearing designs exists to allow the demands of the application to be correctly met for maximum efficiency, reliability, durability, and performance.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] There is no archaeological evidence for this sequence of technological development.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The Egyptian drawings in the tomb of Djehutihotep are believed to show the process of moving massive stone blocks not with rollers but upon sledges pulled over sand which was wetted to increase its cohesion and reduce friction.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] There are also Egyptian drawings of plain bearings used to support the far end of hand drills.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Wheeled vehicles using plain bearings emerged between about 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] A recovered example of an early rolling-element bearing is a wooden ball bearing supporting a rotating table from the remains of the Roman Nemi ships in Lake Nemi, Italy.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Leonardo da Vinci incorporated drawings of ball bearings in his design for a helicopter around the year 1500; this is the first recorded use of bearings in an aerospace design.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] However, Agostino Ramelli is the first to have published roller and thrust bearings sketches.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] An issue with the ball and roller bearings is that the balls or rollers rub against each other, causing additional friction.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] This can be reduced by enclosing each individual ball or roller within a cage.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The captured, or caged, ball bearing was originally described by Galileo in the 17th century.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The first practical caged-roller bearing was invented in the mid-1740s by horologist John Harrison for his H3 marine timekeeper.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In this timepiece, the caged bearing was only used for a very limited oscillating motion, but later on, Harrison applied a similar bearing design with a true rotational movement in a contemporaneous regulator clock.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The first patent on ball bearings was awarded to Philip Vaughan, a Welsh inventor and ironmaster in Carmarthen in 1794.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] His was the first modern ball-bearing design, with the ball running along a groove in the axle assembly.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearings played a pivotal role in the nascent Industrial Revolution, allowing the new industrial machinery to operate efficiently.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For example, they were used for holding wheel and axle assemblies to greatly reduce friction compared to prior non-bearing designs.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The first patent for a radial-style ball bearing was awarded to Jules Suriray, a Parisian bicycle mechanic, on 3 August 1869.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The bearings were then fitted to the winning bicycle ridden by James Moore in the world's first bicycle road race, Paris-Rouen, in November 1869.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In 1883, Friedrich Fischer, founder of FAG, developed an approach for milling and grinding balls of equal size and exact roundness by means of a suitable production machine, which set the stage for the creation of an independent bearing industry.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] His hometown Schweinfurt later became a world-leading center for ball bearing production.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The modern, self-aligning design of ball bearing is attributed to Sven Wingquist of the SKF ball-bearing manufacturer in 1907 when he was awarded Swedish patent No.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Henry Timken, a 19th-century visionary and innovator in carriage manufacturing, patented the tapered roller bearing in 1898.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The following year he formed a company to produce his innovation.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Over a century, the company grew to make bearings of all types, including specialty steel bearings and an array of related products and services.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Erich Franke invented and patented the wire race bearing in 1934.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] His focus was on a bearing design with a cross-section as small as possible and which could be integrated into the enclosing design.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] After World War II, he founded with Gerhard Heydrich the company Franke & Heydrich KG (today Franke GmbH) to push the development and production of wire race bearings.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Richard Stribeck's extensive research on ball bearing steels identified the metallurgy of the commonly used 100Cr6 (AISI 52100), showing coefficient of friction as a function of pressure.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Designed in 1968 and later patented in 1972, Bishop-Wisecarver's co-founder Bud Wisecarver created vee groove bearing guide wheels, a type of linear motion bearing consisting of both an external and internal 90-degree vee angle.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In the early 1980s, Pacific Bearing's founder, Robert Schroeder, invented the first bi-material plain bearing that was interchangeable with linear ball bearings.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] This bearing had a metal shell (aluminum, steel or stainless steel) and a layer of Teflon-based material connected by a thin adhesive layer.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Today's ball and roller bearings are used in many applications, which include a rotating component.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Examples include ultra high-speed bearings in dental drills, aerospace bearings in the Mars Rover, gearbox and wheel bearings on automobiles, flexure bearings in optical alignment systems, and air bearings used in coordinate-measuring machines.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The first plain and rolling-element bearings were wood, closely followed by bronze.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Over their history, bearings have been made of many materials, including ceramic, sapphire, glass, steel, bronze, and other metals.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Plastic bearings made of nylon, polyoxymethylene, polytetrafluoroethylene, and UHMWPE, among other materials, are also in use today.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Watchmakers produce "jeweled" watches using sapphire plain bearings to reduce friction, thus allowing more precise timekeeping.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Even basic materials can have impressive durability.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Wooden bearings, for instance, can still be seen today in old clocks or in water mills where the water provides cooling and lubrication.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] By far, the most common bearing is the plain bearing, a bearing that uses surfaces in rubbing contact, often with a lubricant such as oil or graphite.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] A plain bearing may or may not be a discrete device.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] With suitable lubrication, plain bearings often give acceptable accuracy, life, and friction at minimal cost.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] However, there are many applications where a more suitable bearing can improve efficiency, accuracy, service intervals, reliability, speed of operation, size, weight, and costs of purchasing and operating machinery.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Thus, many types of bearings have varying shapes, materials, lubrication, principle of operation, and so on.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The following table summarizes the notable characteristics of each of these bearing types.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Reducing friction in bearings is often important for efficiency, to reduce wear and to facilitate extended use at high speeds and to avoid overheating and premature failure of the bearing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Essentially, a bearing can reduce friction by virtue of its shape, by its material, or by introducing and containing a fluid between surfaces or by separating the surfaces with an electromagnetic field.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Combinations of these can even be employed within the same bearing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] An example is where the cage is made of plastic, and it separates the rollers/balls, which reduce friction by their shape and finish.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearing design varies depending on the size and directions of the forces required to support.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Forces can be predominately radial, axial (thrust bearings), or bending moments perpendicular to the main axis.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Different bearing types have different operating speed limits.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Speed is typically specified as maximum relative surface speeds, often specified ft/s or m/s.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Rotational bearings typically describe performance in terms of the product *DN* where *D* is the mean diameter (often in mm) of the bearing and *N* is the rotation rate in revolutions per minute.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Generally, there is considerable speed range overlap between bearing types.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Plain bearings typically handle only lower speeds, rolling element bearings are faster, followed by fluid bearings and finally magnetic bearings which are limited ultimately by centripetal force overcoming material strength.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Some applications apply bearing loads from varying directions and accept only limited play or "slop" as the applied load changes.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] One source of motion is gaps or "play" in the bearing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For example, a 10 mm shaft in a 12 mm hole has 2 mm play.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Allowable play varies greatly depending on the use.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] As an example, a wheelbarrow wheel supports radial and axial loads.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Axial loads may be hundreds of newtons force left or right, and it is typically acceptable for the wheel to wobble by as much as 10 mm under the varying load.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In contrast, a lathe may position a cutting tool to ±0.002 mm using a ball lead screw held by rotating bearings.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Stiffness is the amount that the gap varies when the load on the bearing changes, distinct from the friction of the bearing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] A second source of motion is elasticity in the bearing itself.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For example, the balls in a ball bearing are like stiff rubber and under load deform from a round to a slightly flattened shape.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The race is also elastic and develops a slight dent where the ball presses on it.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The stiffness of a bearing is how the distance between the parts separated by the bearing varies with the applied load.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] With rolling element bearings, this is due to the strain of the ball and race.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] With fluid bearings, it is due to how the pressure of the fluid varies with the gap (when correctly loaded, fluid bearings are typically stiffer than rolling element bearings).
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Some bearings use a thick grease for lubrication, which is pushed into the gaps between the bearing surfaces, also known as *packing*.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The grease is held in place by a plastic, leather, or rubber gasket (also called a *gland*) that covers the inside and outside edges of the bearing race to keep the grease from escaping.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearings may also be packed with other materials.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Historically, the wheels on railroad cars used sleeve bearings packed with *waste* or loose scraps of cotton or wool fiber soaked in oil, then later used solid pads of cotton.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearings can be lubricated by a ring oiler, a metal ring that rides loosely on the central rotating shaft of the bearing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The ring hangs down into a chamber containing lubricating oil.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] As the bearing rotates, viscous adhesion draws oil up the ring and onto the shaft, where the oil migrates into the bearing to lubricate it.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Excess oil is flung off and collects in the pool again.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] A rudimentary form of lubrication is splash lubrication.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Some machines contain a pool of lubricant in the bottom, with gears partially immersed in the liquid, or crank rods that can swing down into the pool as the device operates.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The spinning wheels fling oil into the air around them, while the crank rods slap at the surface of the oil, splashing it randomly on the engine's interior surfaces.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Some small internal combustion engines specifically contain special plastic *flinger wheels* which randomly scatter oil around the interior of the mechanism.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For high-speed and high-power machines, a loss of lubricant can result in rapid bearing heating and damage due to friction.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Also, in dirty environments, the oil can become contaminated with dust or debris, increasing friction.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In these applications, a fresh supply of lubricant can be continuously supplied to the bearing and all other contact surfaces, and the excess can be collected for filtration, cooling, and possibly reuse.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Pressure oiling is commonly used in large and complex internal combustion engines in parts of the engine where directly splashed oil cannot reach, such as up into overhead valve assemblies.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] High-speed turbochargers also typically require a pressurized oil system to cool the bearings and keep them from burning up due to the heat from the turbine.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Composite bearings are designed with a self-lubricating polytetrafluorethylene (PTFE) liner with a laminated metal backing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The PTFE liner offers consistent, controlled friction as well as durability, whilst the metal backing ensures the composite bearing is robust and capable of withstanding high loads and stresses throughout its long life.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Its design also makes it lightweight-one tenth the weight of a traditional rolling element bearing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] There are many methods of mounting bearings, usually involving an interference fit.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] When press fitting or shrink fitting a bearing into a bore or onto a shaft, it's important to keep the housing bore and shaft outer diameter to very close limits, which can involve one or more counterboring operations, several facing operations, and drilling, tapping, and threading operations.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Alternatively, an interference fit can also be achieved with the addition of a tolerance ring.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The service life of the bearing is affected by many factors not controlled by the bearing manufacturers.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For example, bearing mounting, temperature, exposure to external environment, lubricant cleanliness, and electrical currents through bearings.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] High frequency PWM inverters can induce electric currents in a bearing, which can be suppressed by the use of ferrite chokes.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The temperature and terrain of the micro-surface will determine the amount of friction by touching solid parts.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Certain elements and fields reduce friction while increasing speeds.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Strength and mobility help determine the load the bearing type can carry.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Alignment factors can play a damaging role in wear and tear, yet overcome by computer aid signaling and non-rubbing bearing types, such as magnetic levitation or air field pressure.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Fluid and magnetic bearings can have practically indefinite service lives.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In practice, fluid bearings support high loads in hydroelectric plants that have been in nearly continuous service since about 1900 and show no signs of wear.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Rolling element bearing life is determined by load, temperature, maintenance, lubrication, material defects, contamination, handling, installation and other factors.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] These factors can all have a significant effect on bearing life.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearing life is statistical: several samples of a given bearing will often exhibit a bell curve of service life, with a few samples showing significantly better or worse life.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearing life varies because microscopic structure and contamination vary greatly even where macroscopically they seem identical.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The L10/B10 life of the bearing is theoretical, and may not represent service life of the bearing.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearings are also rated using the C0 (static loading) value.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] This is the basic load rating as a reference, and not an actual load value.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For plain bearings, some materials give a much longer life than others.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Some of the John Harrison clocks still operate after hundreds of years because of the *lignum vitae* wood employed in their construction, whereas his metal clocks are seldom run due to potential wear.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Flexure bearings rely on elastic properties of a material.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Flexure bearings bend a piece of material repeatedly.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Some materials fail after repeated bending, even at low loads, but careful material selection and bearing design can make flexure bearing life indefinite.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Although long bearing life is often desirable, it is sometimes not necessary.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Harris 2001 describes a bearing for a rocket motor oxygen pump that gave several hours life, far in excess of the several tens of minutes needed.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Depending on the customized specifications (backing material and PTFE compounds), composite bearings can operate up to 30 years without maintenance.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For bearings which are used in oscillating applications, customized approaches to calculate L10/B10 are used.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Many bearings require periodic maintenance to prevent premature failure, but others require little maintenance.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The latter include various kinds of polymer, fluid and magnetic bearings, as well as rolling-element bearings that are described with terms including *sealed bearing* and *sealed for life*.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] These contain seals to keep the dirt out and the grease in.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] They work successfully in many applications, providing maintenance-free operation.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Some applications cannot use them effectively.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Nonsealed bearings often have a grease fitting, for periodic lubrication with a grease gun, or an oil cup for periodic filling with oil.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Before the 1970s, sealed bearings were not encountered on most machinery, and oiling and greasing were a more common activity than they are today.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] For example, automotive chassis used to require "lube jobs" nearly as often as engine oil changes, but today's car chassis are mostly sealed for life.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] From the late 1700s through the mid-1900s, industry relied on many workers called oilers to lubricate machinery frequently with oil cans.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Factory machines today usually have *lube systems*, in which a central pump serves periodic charges of oil or grease from a reservoir through *lube lines* to the various *lube points* in the machine's bearing surfaces, bearing journals, pillow blocks, and so on.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The timing and number of such *lube cycles* is controlled by the machine's computerized control, such as PLC or CNC, as well as by manual override functions when occasionally needed.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] This automated process is how all modern CNC machine tools and many other factory machines are lubricated.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Similar lube systems are also used on nonautomated machines, in which case there is a hand pump that a machine operator is supposed to pump once daily (for machines in constant use) or once weekly.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] These are called *one-shot systems* from their chief selling point: one pull on one handle to lube the whole machine, instead of a dozen pumps of an alemite gun or oil can in a dozen different positions around the machine.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The oiling system inside a modern automotive or truck engine is similar in concept to the lube systems mentioned above, except that oil is pumped continuously.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Much of this oil flows through passages drilled or cast into the engine block and cylinder heads, escaping through ports directly onto bearings and squirting elsewhere to provide an oil bath.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The oil pump simply pumps constantly, and any excess pumped oil continuously escapes through a relief valve back into the sump.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Many bearings in high-cycle industrial operations need periodic lubrication and cleaning, and many require occasional adjustment, such as pre-load adjustment, to minimize the effects of wear.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Bearing life is often much better when the bearing is kept clean and well-lubricated.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] However, many applications make good maintenance difficult.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] One example is bearings in the conveyor of a rock crusher are exposed continually to hard abrasive particles.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Cleaning is of little use because cleaning is expensive, yet the bearing is contaminated again as soon as the conveyor resumes operation.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Thus, a good maintenance program might lubricate the bearings frequently but not include any disassembly for cleaning.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] The frequent lubrication, by its nature, provides a limited kind of cleaning action by displacing older (grit-filled) oil or grease with a fresh charge, which itself collects grit before being displaced by the next cycle.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] Another example are bearings in wind turbines, which makes maintenance difficult since the nacelle is placed high up in the air in strong wind areas.
[src:aeolipile/bearing-mechanical] In addition, the turbine does not always run and is subjected to different operating behavior in different weather conditions, which makes proper lubrication a challenge.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] He made several important inventions, including a diving apparatus, and introduced the paddle wheel as a substitute for oars.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] From 1539 to 1543, he built and tested a series of paddle wheelers propelled by human action, the most notorious being the carrack *Trinidad*, which performed excellently in its test run in the harbor of Barcelona.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] Despite his success, his inventions were never implemented due to political rivalry and skepticism about their practicality.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] In the nineteenth century, a Spanish archivist claimed to have discovered documents that showed that de Garay had tested a steam-powered ship in 1543.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] However, these claims have been discredited by the Spanish authorities.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] It has been proposed that González mistook a steam-powered desalinator created by Garay for a steam boiler.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] There is no record of Blasco de Garay's birth or of his familial connections except for the mention in his memorial of an older brother, a Diego de Alarcon, who lost his life as an army captain in Italy.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] At the time there were several people of the Garay name who distinguished themselves in letters and in the military service who seem to have been from the minor nobility in the Castilian city of Toledo.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] That his brother's name was in the Castilian form "Diego" (James) supports a Castilian origin.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] The most plausible account is that he was an impoverished minor nobleman, educated in letters, who out of necessity went into the King's service but, as he wrote, dedicated himself to the sciences and invention.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] Another device to detect objects on the seabed with the naked eye.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] A way to keep a light burning underwater.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] The attribution to Blasco de Garay of the testing of a steam engine made on a boat in the port of Barcelona was claimed in 1825 by Tomás González, director of the royal archives of Simancas, to the distinguished historian Martín Fernández Navarrete.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] González stated that in a file he had found, there is documentation endorsing a test conducted June 17, 1543 by the Naval Captain and Engineer of the navy of Charles V of a navigation system with no sails or oars containing a *large copper of boiling water*.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] Navarrete published González's account in 1826 in *Baron de Zach's Astronomical Correspondence*.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] "Blasco de Garay, a captain in the navy, proposed in 1543, to the Emperor and King, Charles the Fifth, a machine to propel large boats and ships, even in calm weather, without oars or sails.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] , which in fact took place on the 17th on the month of June, of the said year 1543.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] Garay would not explain the particulars of his discovery: it was evident however during the experiment that it consisted in a large copper of boiling water, and in moving wheels attached to either side of the ship.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] , which came from Colibre to discharge a cargo of corn at Barcelona, of which Peter de Scarza was captain.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] In the reports made to the emperor and to the prince, this ingenious invention was generally approved, particularly on account of the promptness and facility with which the ship was made to go about.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] in three hours that the machine was complicated and expensive and that there would be an exposure to danger in case the boiler should burst.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] The other commissioners affirmed that the vessel tacked with the same rapidity as a galley maneuvered in the ordinary way, and went at least a league an hour.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] "As soon as the experiment was made Garay took the whole machine with which he had furnished the vessel, leaving only the wooden part in the arsenal at Barcelona, and keeping all the rest for himself.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] "In spite of Ravago's opposition, the invention was approved, and if the expedition in which Charles the Vth was then engaged had not prevented, he would no doubt have encouraged it.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] Jerónimo de Ayanz y Beaumont, a Spanish soldier, painter, cosmographer, musician, and above all, inventor, registered in 1606 the first patent for a steam machine, so he is credited as the inventor of all kinds of steam machines.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] Steamboats were in fact not introduced to Spain until 1817.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] *Real Fernando*, launched in 1817 and which plied the Guadalquivir River from Sevilla to Sanlucar, was probably the first steamboat built in Spain.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] She was joined by PS *Hope*, built at Bristol in 1813.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] The belated claims made on behalf of Blasco de Garay have since been discredited by the Spanish authorities.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] The failure to find documentation confirming that letter led to a controversy between French and Spanish scholars.
[src:aeolipile/blasco-de-garay] The issue gained such popularity that Honoré de Balzac wrote a comedy, made of five acts, with the theme as an argument entitled *Les Ressources de Quinola* which premiered in Paris on March 19, 1842 and which tended to be sympathetic to the Spanish claim.
